6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"KuCoin uses traditional 8-hour funding intervals based on premium/discount to spot price, calculated from order book imbalances. GMX employs hourly funding rates determined by open interest skew between long and short positions, with rates paid directly from the GLP pool. KuCoin's rates tend to be more volatile during high momentum periods, while GMX maintains more predictable funding patterns due to its pool-based architecture. GMX's hourly settlements provide more frequent arbitrage opportunities but require active monitoring."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lb",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange offers better funding rate arbitrage opportunities?","answer":"GMX provides more frequent opportunities with hourly funding, while KuCoin offers potentially larger spreads during volatile periods. GMX's predictable mechanics favor systematic strategies, whereas KuCoin rewards timing market momentum."},{"question":"How do the settlement mechanisms affect arbitrage execution?","answer":"KuCoin uses traditional cross-margin settlement every 8 hours, allowing for standard delta-neutral strategies. GMX's oracle-based system settles hourly but introduces smart contract risk and potential oracle manipulation during extreme market conditions."},{"question":"What are the key liquidity differences for perpetual futures?","answer":"KuCoin provides order book liquidity with typical bid-ask spreads, especially strong for altcoins. GMX uses pooled liquidity which can result in price impact for large trades but eliminates traditional slippage concerns for smaller positions."},{"question":"Which platform has lower overall costs for funding rate arbitrage?","answer":"KuCoin generally offers lower fees (0.02% maker) compared to GMX (0.05% minimum). However, GMX's lack of traditional slippage and gas optimization on Arbitrum can offset higher base fees for smaller position sizes."}]}]
